text: I don't get the people complaining that it's a remake - yeah it is a remake, they never shied away from that fact, they never acted like it wasn't a remake of the original - the original people are okay with it, David Belle loved and enjoyed making this one - everyone is happy and they had a good time, isn't that what matters? So what if this is a remake, it's not trying to replace anything, your original film still exists, it's still a good movie, and now there's just an English one - it's not some competition - these guys make this movie because they loved what they do so why not stop the complaints and comparisons and just watch and have fun - both the original and the remake can co-exist, the people who made both movies can accept that so why can't you all >.>

author: Doug Glatt

text: An American remake of District B-13, almost shot for shot, but instead it is with the late, Paul Walker, and they have The RZA playing the main villain only his name isn't Taj but the titular character, Brick Mansions.  All I got to say ab...out this is where in the blueberry muffin nut berries is Officer Damien, where is Cyril Raffelli?  Don't get me wrong, Paul looks like he plays this part well and commits to it naturally but still when I see this I see don't see anything other than a straight up remake of District B-13.  Oh well, at least they managed to keep in and cast the father of Park'our himself Mister David Belle himself reprising himself as the same character he played in the French version.  And from what I saw in the trailer it almost looks like that Rza's character, Brick Mansions, the main villain looks almost more fleshed out than in the French version.  At least in this movie that more of the other members of the crew have a little more flesh and life breathed into them (in the original District B-13 movie the only Taj henchmen that had life was K-2 played by the late Tony Amarro...I think that is how he spell his name.)  And to their credit it does look like that Paul Walker's character and David Belle have more of a chemistry for playing off of each other than Cyril and Belle in the original.  I think that I am 50/50 on this movie. I want to buy this but I am being hesitantly wanting to get into this. I am approaching this with caution.

text: if I remember rightly parkour and this yamakasi stuff originated in suburban paris. why should you relocate the scene to detroit? i think it's was somehow charming and original to make a film that combines the french parkour culture with an action script and a dark vision of the future prospect of french banlieus and also with an slightly exaggerated criticism of the french society and the way it deals the generations of immigrants, living in these banlieus. i mean, sometimes (and i would say even in this  case!) it makes sense, that a story takes place at a certain place and time in a specific culture. this movie might be not bad at all, but i really wonder if the bulk of the american audience has not already seen the 2004 original?! I'm still waiting for a remake of "the live of others". I wonder how they will transport this into an american setting...but thinking about current events...i just had a great idea for an remake!...

text: WTF is this?! I only recently heard about this movie (as I'm not a huge fan of Paul Walker or B13) and I was kinda pumped. But after seeing this trailer, facepalm. I mean, I know I'm suppose to feel sympathy for Paul Walker and all (who died 3 months ago in a car accident) because this is his last movie (I don't know how much of him is gonna be in F&F7) and believe me I am. His death was a tragic loss but lets put that aside, be serious and talk about the movie. I'm up for an American remake of B13. Of course, same plot and characters but that's not what the original movie was about so that's ok. It was about action sequences and stunts. Looking at the trailer not only are they remaking the movie but they're replicating all the awesome stunts (and possibly reusing some scenes) from the original. This is STUPID! Even the remake of The Karate Kid had different fighting moves than the original. If they're gonna remake B13, at least choreograph different fight scenes. We don't need to see the same parkour moves or fighting style, we just want action. However it is choreographed is fine with me (as long as it's different) because it could be just as awesome (if not better) than the original. David Belle's English is bad to but that's forgivable. The problem with remakes is that they replicate everything in the original without changing enough to stand on it's own and this is gonna be one of those POINTLESS remakes. I know that sounds ignorant (because the movie isn't even out yet) but the trailer gave everything away and that's never a good sign!

text: Awesome finally a movie that Depicts Detroit true form of American Grit!!! Funny is that the Brick Mansions known to Detroiters as the Brewster-Douglas Projects is a real place, has finally been torn down in the last month :) QUICK HISTORY NOTES: The complex was home to such notable figures as Diana Ross, Mary Wilson, Florence Ballard, Lily Tomlin, Loni Love, and Etterlene DeBarge, during their early years. The claymation animated series, The PJs, was based on the Brewster Douglas project, as well. It was also seen in a screenshots for the movie Dreamgirls, as well as D12's debut music video. RuPaul mentions the Brewster Projects in the intro of the 1992 song, "Supermodel (You Better Work)". Brick Mansions was the nation’s first federally funded public housing development for African Americans and longest lasting.

Gabalot is a social media site to discuss plots, characters, themes, and everything else that transpires in movies, books, and TV shows.  This site gives users the ability to discuss spoilers with others on topics that may range from theories in upcoming TV show episodes to how a non-fiction work of literature has impacted their life.  Our goal is to make entertainment experiences more connected with other people around the world.  There are comment boards and forums all over the internet, and we would like to unify them into one main social media site.
